Ah, don't worry about the hardware-side of things too much.  Writing an interesting game is more of an achievement then building a simple memory storage interface.  You can put a read and a write routine in your game, and just by changing those 2 routines later (the hardware dudes will supply the code), it could read and write from any hardware.  For modest amount of testing of your save/load, you could just keep it in a .SAV file and hex edit the data in and out manually, as most of the needed testing will be for the PPU and game logic, I'm sure.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Sat Sep 25, 2010 2:21 pm</p><hr />
