<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6971&amp;p=67815#p67815"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Transferring data from Cart-&gt;Cart?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6971&amp;p=67815#p67815"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Xious wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />How would you get the data to them? You'd need a way to interface your storage device with a PC, upload the data to a hard drive or other storage card, then e-mail it. This means creating a USB link between your dongle and a PC, which may be as complex as using an SD card on the game cartridge.<br /></div><br />Sometimes you want a no-copy flag so that someone doesn't clone your personal information. Games also want to deter item-cloning exploits that could wreck the in-game economy. Console-oriented memory cards support no-copy flags by allowing files to be moved from one memory card. SD cards ordinarily don't support this. That's why you can move Animal Crossing 1 (GameCube) files from one card to another but not Animal Crossing 3 (Wii) files. In theory, SD cards support a no-copy flag called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_Protection_for_Recordable_Media" class="postlink">CPRM</a>, but next to no reader devices support CPRM, and in any case, it's cost prohibitive for a hobbyist to license.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />It's a simple manner to back-up whatever you have on the card and it you lose it, or it is damaged, you can replace it.<br /></div><br />How many caught Mew, how many Master Balls, and how many Rare Candies do you want the player to be able to restore from backup?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Additionally, SD cards are pretty tough. I've only had one die.<br /></div><br />I've had a USB flash drive, an SD card, and two SD card readers die. The SD card was not of the "folding" type (which, as I understand it, is pretty much RS-MMC with another piece of plastic hanging off it).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Many systems today have only USB and micro-card ports, so serial is out, and if the USB controller doesn't recognize it and its data natively (using built-in or existing software drivers), then you'll need specialized software to view and extract it, which you'd have to make multi-platform (PC, Mac PPC/x86 dual-binary//Linux) in order to ensure market durability.<br /></div><br />PowerPC may no longer be necessary. All Macs sold in the past four years are Intel. How long does Apple plan to support 10.5 (Leopard)? Free operating systems such as Linux will never support CPRM.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Sep 25, 2010 8:30 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
